**1.** A computer-implemented method for issuing a community tax certificate and related permits as a digital credential, comprising:
    (a) receiving, via a user digital wallet, an application request comprising user identity data and permit parameters;
    (b) transmitting said application request to a Machine Learning Eligibility Engine (ML-ERE);
    (c) executing, by the ML-ERE, a multi-modal ensemble algorithm comprising a Gradient Boosting Decision Tree and a Recurrent Neural Network to analyze said user identity data against historical compliance records and real-time risk indicators, thereby generating a dynamic Trust Score ($T_s$);
    (d) determining an issuance status based on said $T_s$ relative to a predefined threshold;
    (e) upon a positive determination, instantiating a Smart Contract on a permissioned blockchain network configured to hold a payment escrow;
    (f) receiving a payment authorization from said user digital wallet to said Smart Contract;
    (g) verifying, by the Smart Contract, the successful settlement of said payment;
    (h) triggering, by the Smart Contract, an Issuer Authority Node to cryptographically sign a Verifiable Credential (VC) containing the permit details and a hash of the payment transaction; and
    (i) transmitting said signed VC to said user digital wallet for storage, wherein the VC is verifiable by third parties without contacting the Issuer Authority Node.

**6.** A system for automated civic permit issuance, comprising:
    (a) a processor and a memory storing instructions that, when executed, cause the processor to:
    (i) interface with a user digital wallet to receive application data;
    (ii) deploy a Machine Learning model trained on historical municipal tax data to predict the probability of compliance and fraud;
    (iii) interact with a blockchain network to execute a payment smart contract; and
    (iv) generate a cryptographically signed Verifiable Credential;
    (b) a blockchain network comprising a plurality of nodes, wherein at least one node acts as an Issuer Authority and at least one node acts as a Validator for payment transactions;
    (c) a database of historical compliance records accessible by the Machine Learning model; and
    (d) a verification module configured to validate the cryptographic signature and the Zero-Knowledge Proof of the Verifiable Credential without requiring a query to the central database.

**11.** A method for verifying a community tax certificate, comprising:
    (a) receiving a Verifiable Credential from a user digital wallet;
    (b) extracting the cryptographic signature and the Zero-Knowledge Proof from the credential;
    (c) verifying the signature against a public key of the Issuer Authority Node stored on a blockchain;
    (d) validating the Zero-Knowledge Proof to confirm the credential is valid and not revoked without revealing the underlying user data; and
    (e) confirming the payment transaction hash embedded in the credential matches a confirmed transaction on the blockchain ledger.

**15.** A computer-implemented method for detecting fraud in community tax issuance, comprising:
    (a) ingesting a stream of application requests;
    (b) applying a Graph Neural Network (GNN) to map relationships between applicants, devices, and IP addresses to identify clusters of coordinated fraud;
    (c) cross-referencing said clusters with the output of the ML-ERE; and
    (d) automatically freezing the Smart Contract associated with any application linked to a high-risk cluster, preventing payment processing and credential issuance.

